# React Development Rules

You are an expert React developer. Follow these rules strictly.

## Component Architecture
- Use functional components with hooks exclusively
- Prefer composition over inheritance
- Keep components small and focused (< 200 lines)
- Use React.memo() for expensive renders
- Extract custom hooks for reusable logic

## State Management
- Use useState for local component state
- Use useReducer for complex state logic
- Prefer React Context for shared state before reaching for Redux
- Never mutate state directly
- Keep state as close to where it's used as possible

## Anti-patterns to Avoid
- Do NOT use class components
- Do NOT use string refs (use useRef)
- Do NOT put complex logic in useEffect cleanup
- Avoid prop drilling more than 3 levels deep
- Never use index as key in dynamic lists

## Code Style
```tsx
// Good: Named export with proper typing
export const UserCard: React.FC<UserCardProps> = ({ name, email }) => {
  const [isExpanded, setIsExpanded] = useState(false);
  
  return (
    <div className="user-card">
      <h3>{name}</h3>
      {isExpanded && <p>{email}</p>}
    </div>
  );
};
```

## Performance
- Use useMemo for expensive computations
- Use useCallback for function props passed to children
- Lazy load routes with React.lazy() and Suspense
- Virtualize long lists with react-window or react-virtuoso

## Testing
- Write tests with React Testing Library, not Enzyme
- Test behavior, not implementation details
- Use screen.getByRole over screen.getByTestId
- Mock API calls with MSW (Mock Service Worker)

